WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.382 --> 00:00:04.090
ADAM QUAYLE: Thanks
for coming, everyone.

00:00:04.090 --> 00:00:06.610
I'm Adam Quayle, and
I'm really excited to be

00:00:06.610 --> 00:00:09.750
hosting Ashanti Branch today.

00:00:09.750 --> 00:00:12.310
Ashanti is a lot of things.

00:00:12.310 --> 00:00:14.780
He's the founder and
executive director

00:00:14.780 --> 00:00:17.760
of the Ever Forward Club,
which we'll learn about today.

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:22.420
He's also an education fellow
at the Stanford d.school.

00:00:22.420 --> 00:00:26.760
And he's also assistant
principal at Montero Middle

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:28.880
School in the East Bay.

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:30.960
And so today Ashanti
is going to take us

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:32.840
through the Taking
Off the Mask exercise.

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:35.410
So I hope you're all
ready to get really

00:00:35.410 --> 00:00:37.440
real with your
coworkers, because it's

00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:38.960
going to get real in here.

00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:42.610
And then we're going to learn
a little bit about how the Ever

00:00:42.610 --> 00:00:46.914
Forward Club is helping young
men in the East Bay and beyond.

00:00:46.914 --> 00:00:48.830
And you'll hear from
some of the students that

00:00:48.830 --> 00:00:50.410
have benefit directly from it.

00:00:50.410 --> 00:00:52.800
So with that I'd love to
welcome Ashanti Branch.

00:00:59.214 --> 00:01:00.505
ASHANTI BRANCH: Good afternoon.

00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:05.990
So Adam probably made you a
little nervous when he's like,

00:01:05.990 --> 00:01:09.375
are you ready to get
real with your coworkers?

00:01:09.375 --> 00:01:11.250
I think that when we
talk about getting real,

00:01:11.250 --> 00:01:14.160
sometimes that's a very--
it means different things

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:16.100
to different people.

00:01:16.100 --> 00:01:18.270
So we're not going
to start there.

00:01:18.270 --> 00:01:21.760
I'm gonna start by getting
really real with you about me.

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:27.970
So I'm more nervous than usual
because my mom's in the room.

00:01:27.970 --> 00:01:30.954
And she's never heard
me present before.

00:01:30.954 --> 00:01:32.870
I don't know if she's
ever watched me present,

00:01:32.870 --> 00:01:35.100
but I know she's never
been to one of my talks--

00:01:35.100 --> 00:01:36.710
at least my new talk.

00:01:36.710 --> 00:01:38.680
And I talk a lot about her.

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:40.800
So this morning I
was like, oh, man.

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:42.305
How do I change that talk?

00:01:45.210 --> 00:01:47.530
How do I not say
all the stuff I say?

00:01:49.732 --> 00:01:51.440
And I had to call her
yesterday for help.

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:53.470
I had to call her
yesterday for help.

00:01:53.470 --> 00:01:55.330
As an adult man,
I had to call her

00:01:55.330 --> 00:01:57.240
because I didn't have
enough drivers to get

00:01:57.240 --> 00:01:59.420
all the young men
here, and so I had

00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:02.520
to ask her for help yesterday.

00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:04.505
And she said, OK.

00:02:04.505 --> 00:02:07.130
And so I said, well, why would
I change the talk to try and not

00:02:07.130 --> 00:02:12.500
talk about her when the reason
I'm standing here alive, free,

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:16.728
educated is because of her?

00:02:16.728 --> 00:02:19.530
Of her sacrifice?

00:02:19.530 --> 00:02:24.450
My father died three
months before I was born.

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:27.629
His father died three
months before he died.

00:02:27.629 --> 00:02:29.170
So six months leading
up to my birth,

00:02:29.170 --> 00:02:33.510
I lost both my
grandfather and my father,

00:02:33.510 --> 00:02:35.890
and no one gave me a
choice in the matter.

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:37.500
I just showed up
here on the Earth,

00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:42.280
out of Bates hospital, popped
out, and there was problems.

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:44.430
Like, if you handed me
a checklist in the womb,

00:02:44.430 --> 00:02:46.346
and I had a choice, I
would have chosen things

00:02:46.346 --> 00:02:48.540
that looked pretty different.

00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:51.050
Like I would have chosen
to have two parents,

00:02:51.050 --> 00:02:52.480
to maybe live in a house.

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:57.450
To maybe live in a community
where being smart was OK.

00:02:57.450 --> 00:03:00.330
Or like being your best wasn't
like making other people feel

00:03:00.330 --> 00:03:03.220
bad, but being your
best was absolutely--

00:03:03.220 --> 00:03:07.110
people were pushing you to
be better than your best.

00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:08.926
But I didn't get that, either.

00:03:08.926 --> 00:03:10.810
So I grew up in
Oakland, California.

00:03:10.810 --> 00:03:12.560
I knew there were
certain ways I had

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:18.640
to behave and act that would
give me either respect, or not.

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:20.310
And there was a very
short list of what

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:23.180
it meant to be a
man-- a boy growing

00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:25.825
into be a man-- in
Oakland, where I grew up.

00:03:25.825 --> 00:03:27.700
Like when you're a boy,
you have to be a man.

00:03:27.700 --> 00:03:30.460
Like they're
telling you, man up.

00:03:30.460 --> 00:03:31.840
Be tough.

00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:34.365
Don't show no emotions.

00:03:34.365 --> 00:03:38.410
Can you imagine my first
day of fourth grade,

00:03:38.410 --> 00:03:40.690
showing up at a
new school, excited

00:03:40.690 --> 00:03:42.390
to be in this new
school in the hills.

00:03:42.390 --> 00:03:43.770
It was incredible.

00:03:43.770 --> 00:03:45.360
There was no apartments
around there.

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:46.310
It was all houses.

00:03:46.310 --> 00:03:48.550
It was beautiful.

00:03:48.550 --> 00:03:52.460
I had a fight my first
day of fourth grade

00:03:52.460 --> 00:03:54.410
because a guy was like,
we're playing tag.

00:03:54.410 --> 00:03:56.070
Fourth graders play tag, right?

00:03:56.070 --> 00:03:56.940
We're playing tag.

00:03:56.940 --> 00:03:57.621
He tags me.

00:03:57.621 --> 00:03:58.121
I said, OK.

00:03:58.121 --> 00:03:58.621
I'm in.

00:03:58.621 --> 00:03:59.770
You should be running.

00:03:59.770 --> 00:04:02.012
But he tags me again.

00:04:02.012 --> 00:04:03.470
I said, why do you
keep tagging me?

00:04:03.470 --> 00:04:05.922
I'm already it.

00:04:05.922 --> 00:04:08.130
He tags me again, and I
realized he's not tagging me.

00:04:08.130 --> 00:04:10.380
He's hitting me.

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:11.890
Now, I also know certain rules.

00:04:11.890 --> 00:04:13.870
At fourth grade, I
already know that if I

00:04:13.870 --> 00:04:16.020
let this keep
happening-- this is

00:04:16.020 --> 00:04:17.910
in the moment of a
couple of seconds.

00:04:17.910 --> 00:04:18.970
I'm processing.

00:04:18.970 --> 00:04:21.750
If I let this keep happening,
everybody at this new school

00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:24.887
is going to think they
could be hitting me.

00:04:24.887 --> 00:04:25.720
I don't wanna fight.

00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:27.740
I don't even like to fight.

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:30.960
But in that moment, I knew
that something had to happen.

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:34.400
I can either take it and
then be a victim the rest

00:04:34.400 --> 00:04:36.270
of these years in
elementary school,

00:04:36.270 --> 00:04:37.804
or I could do
something about it.

00:04:40.410 --> 00:04:43.450
If you're not the kind of person
who really likes fighting,

00:04:43.450 --> 00:04:46.340
that's a hard decision.

00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:47.740
I was raised by my mother.

00:04:47.740 --> 00:04:50.160
She taught me to be really nice.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:52.280
But nice doesn't work so
well on the playground

00:04:52.280 --> 00:04:55.300
for a young, black boy
growing up in Oakland.

00:04:55.300 --> 00:05:00.120
Being kind and being
gentle doesn't really

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:04.640
help you be looked at as
somebody who people were

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:08.150
like, man, he's incredible.

00:05:08.150 --> 00:05:10.792
Actually, it makes
you look weak, soft.

00:05:10.792 --> 00:05:12.250
They call you many
names that would

00:05:12.250 --> 00:05:14.050
fit in the soft/weak category.

00:05:14.050 --> 00:05:16.850
They're usually
not very positive.

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:21.740
And so I was so thankful
that, throughout elementary,

00:05:21.740 --> 00:05:25.360
you're only in a class with
maybe 25 people, so being smart

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:26.000
is kind of OK.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.042
You can kind of be smart
with those 25 people.

00:05:29.042 --> 00:05:30.850
Not too many people bother you.

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:31.740
But when you get
to middle school,

00:05:31.740 --> 00:05:32.770
it's a whole other
world, because you've

00:05:32.770 --> 00:05:35.130
got 180 kids you got to
deal with, six classes.

00:05:35.130 --> 00:05:36.262
You gotta be in PE.

00:05:36.262 --> 00:05:37.720
You gotta be in
and out of classes.

00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:41.680
You gotta shift your
behavior so many times a day.

00:05:44.570 --> 00:05:47.740
And I learned that
smart wasn't cool.

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:50.620
So even though I maybe,
in my back of my mind,

00:05:50.620 --> 00:05:53.576
though I was smart, that
was not what I was showing.

00:05:53.576 --> 00:05:54.700
Now, for me, math was easy.

00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:55.531
So I could do math.

00:05:55.531 --> 00:05:58.030
We played a lot of math games
at my house, so math was easy.

00:05:58.030 --> 00:06:00.650
So I was passing math
without a problem.

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:02.770
But English-- I didn't
really like English.

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:04.660
I didn't really like
science, history.

00:06:04.660 --> 00:06:06.690
Didn't really like
anything else.

00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:08.960
Didn't really like PE.

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:12.580
So I just did barely enough
so that my mom wouldn't trip--

00:06:12.580 --> 00:06:13.750
so C-.

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:16.220
I can kind of talk
my way out of it.

00:06:16.220 --> 00:06:17.720
Can't come home with no Ds.

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:20.400
Every once in a while
I'd fall into the D range

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:22.800
and couldn't climb out, and
that would be like a half

00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:26.262
hour lecture about something.

00:06:26.262 --> 00:06:27.720
I don't really
remember much of it.

00:06:30.185 --> 00:06:32.560
But I want you know that middle
school, I was in trouble.

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:34.560
If you saw me in
middle school-- if you

00:06:34.560 --> 00:06:36.599
walked to my middle
school campus and saw me,

00:06:36.599 --> 00:06:38.140
you would never have
said, this guy's

00:06:38.140 --> 00:06:41.492
going to speaking to
companies one day.

00:06:41.492 --> 00:06:42.950
You wouldn't be
like, they're going

00:06:42.950 --> 00:06:47.064
to study what this
guy's doing one day,

00:06:47.064 --> 00:06:48.480
because my behavior
was definitely

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:52.920
not leading me to toward
being educated in any way.

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:56.590
And so my life began
to get really chaotic

00:06:56.590 --> 00:06:59.140
in middle school.

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:01.410
Middle school was that
place where you now

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:02.720
are beginning to be tested.

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:03.720
Your body's growing.

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:05.920
Your mind is saying,
hey I want to do this,

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:07.600
but people around you are
saying, you can't do that.

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:09.170
And so you're beginning
trying to figure out

00:07:09.170 --> 00:07:10.320
your world around you.

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:14.667
Getting bullied?

00:07:14.667 --> 00:07:16.500
Having somebody might
take your lunch money?

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:18.340
That was happening.

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:20.160
I couldn't tell mom about it.

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:22.530
First of all, how do
I deal with it myself

00:07:22.530 --> 00:07:26.070
that I let that happen--
that I was afraid enough

00:07:26.070 --> 00:07:29.112
to let somebody take my
money, and I gave it to him.

00:07:31.830 --> 00:07:33.590
That was really
tough to deal with.

00:07:33.590 --> 00:07:35.200
So I kept it to myself.

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:37.199
And I think the only
way she figured it out

00:07:37.199 --> 00:07:39.240
is because every time I'd
come home after school,

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:40.309
I was super hungry.

00:07:40.309 --> 00:07:42.850
And there was already not a lot
of things in the refrigerator

00:07:42.850 --> 00:07:46.050
anyway, so she would know
when something was missing

00:07:46.050 --> 00:07:49.290
because I was eating lunch and
breakfast at the same time,

00:07:49.290 --> 00:07:51.010
kind of.

00:07:51.010 --> 00:07:53.640
And it wasn't until
that moment, where

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:57.082
I was like, this
can't happen anymore.

00:07:57.082 --> 00:07:59.165
Another moment in my life,
being in seventh grade,

00:07:59.165 --> 00:08:00.081
where you're like, OK.

00:08:00.081 --> 00:08:02.460
I gotta stop this
from happening.

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:04.020
What if you're afraid?

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:06.456
What if the people who
are pushing on you,

00:08:06.456 --> 00:08:08.330
making you do something
you don't want to do,

00:08:08.330 --> 00:08:11.796
but you're afraid to
like stand against them?

00:08:11.796 --> 00:08:12.420
What do you do?

00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:18.800
Well, it becomes a very
scary day to have to be like,

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:20.710
I'm actually really
afraid, but I'm actually

00:08:20.710 --> 00:08:23.310
going to have to face this fear
because if this doesn't stop

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:24.622
now, it's going to keep going.

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:30.490
And so it wasn't
until middle school,

00:08:30.490 --> 00:08:32.809
around the eighth grade,
moving into ninth grade, where

00:08:32.809 --> 00:08:36.659
a teacher really
pulled me aside.

00:08:36.659 --> 00:08:40.345
She said, you're
really smart, but you

00:08:40.345 --> 00:08:43.390
don't act like you're not.

00:08:43.390 --> 00:08:45.896
I know that you're upset
that your father died

00:08:45.896 --> 00:08:46.770
before you were born.

00:08:46.770 --> 00:08:48.304
I know that you're
upset about that.

00:08:48.304 --> 00:08:49.470
Maybe you're sad about that.

00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:51.310
I'm like, I ain't sad.

00:08:51.310 --> 00:08:52.990
When she said upset,
I was cool with it.

00:08:52.990 --> 00:08:54.500
I'll be upset,
because you can be

00:08:54.500 --> 00:08:56.845
upset as a young man
in Oakland, but don't

00:08:56.845 --> 00:08:59.870
be talking about me being sad.

00:08:59.870 --> 00:09:02.139
I think deep down
I was really sad.

00:09:02.139 --> 00:09:04.430
When I would see kids get
dropped off by their fathers,

00:09:04.430 --> 00:09:05.874
or get picked up
by their fathers,

00:09:05.874 --> 00:09:07.790
or get chastised by their
fathers, I was like,

00:09:07.790 --> 00:09:08.810
I want that.

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:13.220
And it wasn't till
she said to me,

00:09:13.220 --> 00:09:15.240
life doesn't give
you what you want.

00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:17.550
Life gives you what
you get, and you have

00:09:17.550 --> 00:09:19.820
to make the most out of it.

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:21.865
And in that half hour
lecture she was giving me

00:09:21.865 --> 00:09:25.264
at that moment, that's the
only sentence I remember,

00:09:25.264 --> 00:09:26.680
but it absolutely
changed my life.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:32.090
And so I get my act
together, go to high school.

00:09:32.090 --> 00:09:34.870
I'm going to go to college.

00:09:34.870 --> 00:09:37.170
I hear there's a program
called Upward Bound.

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:38.379
They help you get to college.

00:09:38.379 --> 00:09:40.669
First generation college
student-- I'm like, excellent.

00:09:40.669 --> 00:09:41.801
Turn in my application.

00:09:41.801 --> 00:09:43.800
The lady calls me into
the office and said, hey.

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:44.560
I said, all right.

00:09:44.560 --> 00:09:45.400
Where do I start?

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:47.987
She's like, well, I
have some bad news.

00:09:47.987 --> 00:09:49.070
What do you mean bad news?

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:50.070
I want to go to college.

00:09:50.070 --> 00:09:51.610
You help people get to college.

00:09:51.610 --> 00:09:53.910
She's like, well, you're
not first generation college

00:09:53.910 --> 00:09:54.410
student.

00:09:54.410 --> 00:09:55.672
I was like, of course I am.

00:09:55.672 --> 00:09:58.436
Nobody went to
college in my family.

00:09:58.436 --> 00:10:00.170
She was like, your
mom went to college.

00:10:00.170 --> 00:10:01.545
Your mom's a teacher.

00:10:01.545 --> 00:10:04.500
I'm like, we don't
make no money.

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:06.220
Don't you go to
college to make money?

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:09.500
Why are we broke?

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:12.250
And I knew that day I
would never be a teacher.

00:10:12.250 --> 00:10:14.710
I was clear that I would
never, ever be a teacher.

00:10:14.710 --> 00:10:15.825
I'm like, OK, if I'm
going to college,

00:10:15.825 --> 00:10:18.283
I ain't going to be no teacher,
because teachers don't make

00:10:18.283 --> 00:10:21.410
money, and we got
teachers at my house,

00:10:21.410 --> 00:10:24.210
as much as I love my mom.

00:10:24.210 --> 00:10:26.865
So I went home that day,
pretty upset with her.

00:10:26.865 --> 00:10:29.150
What do you mean,
we went to college

00:10:29.150 --> 00:10:34.570
and we are just barely
able to make it?

00:10:34.570 --> 00:10:36.104
It was an awakening for me.

00:10:36.104 --> 00:10:37.520
So I knew then I
was good at math.

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:39.050
Science started
getting better for me.

00:10:39.050 --> 00:10:40.450
I'm gonna start
paying attention.

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:41.780
I'm going to be an engineer.

00:10:41.780 --> 00:10:44.500
Graduate high school, go to
college for civil engineering.

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:45.930
Start working, making money.

00:10:45.930 --> 00:10:47.090
Great.

00:10:47.090 --> 00:10:49.410
Working, making money--
I could pay rent

00:10:49.410 --> 00:10:53.340
and PG&amp;E the same month and
still have money for food?

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:54.970
That's a big deal.

00:10:54.970 --> 00:10:57.114
That's a big deal.

00:10:57.114 --> 00:10:59.770
But why am I not happy?

00:10:59.770 --> 00:11:02.430
How in the world am I able to--
like, poor boy from Oakland

00:11:02.430 --> 00:11:05.290
goes to college, becomes
an engineer, making money,

00:11:05.290 --> 00:11:08.100
and I'm not happy?

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:11.040
They told me that was what
the secret to happiness was.

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:12.040
You make a lot of money.

00:11:12.040 --> 00:11:16.320
You're gonna go do fun things,
never miss a bachelor party.

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:20.600
You go everywhere
when you have money.

