00:35:49.170 --> 00:35:52.130
As an educator, you know that
you have to show up in class,

00:35:52.130 --> 00:35:55.139
leave the junk in the car, go
up in front of the students,

00:35:55.139 --> 00:35:57.180
be on the show, and when
you get back in the car,

00:35:57.180 --> 00:35:59.250
you can pick it back
up on the way home.

00:36:03.330 --> 00:36:06.260
And I imagine maybe some
of you have to do the same.

00:36:10.420 --> 00:36:13.442
And the question is, do you
just tell everybody everything?

00:36:13.442 --> 00:36:14.900
Like, when they
say, how you doing?

00:36:14.900 --> 00:36:16.450
You say, oh, let me
tell how I'm doing.

00:36:16.450 --> 00:36:16.900
Let me.

00:36:16.900 --> 00:36:17.774
Thank you for asking.

00:36:17.774 --> 00:36:21.139
I've been waiting for
somebody to ask me all day.

00:36:21.139 --> 00:36:22.930
Most times, when people
say, how you doing?

00:36:22.930 --> 00:36:24.550
They are already
like three feet away

00:36:24.550 --> 00:36:27.850
by the time you answer, because
oftentimes we don't really

00:36:27.850 --> 00:36:29.844
mean, how you doing?

00:36:29.844 --> 00:36:31.510
We just have gotten
comfortable with how

00:36:31.510 --> 00:36:34.070
you doing being just
a way to say I'm

00:36:34.070 --> 00:36:37.301
really kind of noticing you.

00:36:37.301 --> 00:36:39.570
Have you ever experienced it?

00:36:39.570 --> 00:36:41.320
Think about it the
next time somebody asks

00:36:41.320 --> 00:36:44.310
you how you're doing,
see if they're actually

00:36:44.310 --> 00:36:46.440
caring how you're doing,
or is it just our way

00:36:46.440 --> 00:36:50.430
of greeting each other?

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:51.260
Try it next time.

00:36:51.260 --> 00:36:52.090
The next time somebody
says, how you doing, say,

00:36:52.090 --> 00:36:53.370
I am so glad you asked.

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:57.380
Let me tell you, and watch them.

00:36:57.380 --> 00:36:58.180
Watch their face.

00:36:58.180 --> 00:37:03.010
They're just gonna
be like-- try it.

00:37:03.010 --> 00:37:03.580
Try it today.

00:37:03.580 --> 00:37:04.829
It'll happen in the afternoon.

00:37:04.829 --> 00:37:05.600
How you doing?

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:07.350
So glad you asked.

00:37:07.350 --> 00:37:08.610
Sit down for some coffee.

00:37:11.320 --> 00:37:15.140
And what I believe is
that, because we are human,

00:37:15.140 --> 00:37:18.920
we say it because it's what
we've been taught as kindness.

00:37:18.920 --> 00:37:21.850
It's just a greeting.

00:37:21.850 --> 00:37:23.870
So how do we deal
with the real stuff?

00:37:23.870 --> 00:37:27.570
When we're in a high-performance
environment, when we're

00:37:27.570 --> 00:37:29.840
in a high-stress environment,
like middle school

00:37:29.840 --> 00:37:32.100
and high school, how do we
deal with the real stuff

00:37:32.100 --> 00:37:35.410
when we can't really
deal with it there?

00:37:35.410 --> 00:37:37.610
I wish that Ever Forward
Club didn't have to exist.

00:37:37.610 --> 00:37:39.180
When I started
teaching, I was barely

00:37:39.180 --> 00:37:40.360
learning the teaching thing.

00:37:40.360 --> 00:37:42.410
I wasn't trying to start
anything on the side,

00:37:42.410 --> 00:37:44.900
but the teaching
wasn't reaching them,

00:37:44.900 --> 00:37:47.410
because they were trying to
pretend that the baggage wasn't

00:37:47.410 --> 00:37:51.240
real, that they were showing up
to school super silly, happy,

00:37:51.240 --> 00:37:55.550
whatever they were doing,
but they had a harder filter.

00:37:55.550 --> 00:37:57.800
Their filter was harder, so
it was kind of leaking out

00:37:57.800 --> 00:37:59.820
into their day-to-day actions.

00:37:59.820 --> 00:38:01.630
As adults, we have
more practice.

00:38:01.630 --> 00:38:03.950
We know, hey, I'm not
showing none of that.

00:38:03.950 --> 00:38:05.696
I'll go in and get myself ready.

00:38:05.696 --> 00:38:07.070
None of that
happened last night.

00:38:07.070 --> 00:38:07.630
That didn't happen.

00:38:07.630 --> 00:38:10.213
That didn't really just happen
this morning on my way to work.

00:38:10.213 --> 00:38:12.160
It didn't happen.

00:38:12.160 --> 00:38:13.940
I didn't just get that
text at lunch time.

00:38:13.940 --> 00:38:14.720
It didn't happen.

00:38:14.720 --> 00:38:17.290
Let me just get back to work.

00:38:19.800 --> 00:38:21.290
And so what I've
learned, and what

00:38:21.290 --> 00:38:22.750
we have learned in
Ever Forward, is

00:38:22.750 --> 00:38:25.390
that providing these young
men a safe space to talk

00:38:25.390 --> 00:38:29.260
about what's really
going on in a safe space.

00:38:29.260 --> 00:38:31.940
I don't expect them to be able
to talk about that stuff out

00:38:31.940 --> 00:38:32.440
there.

00:38:32.440 --> 00:38:33.100
Not yet.

00:38:33.100 --> 00:38:34.670
Our society's not
ready for young men

00:38:34.670 --> 00:38:39.750
to be totally into
their emotions.

00:38:39.750 --> 00:38:41.400
There can be an anger.

00:38:41.400 --> 00:38:42.450
Anger gets you respect.

00:38:42.450 --> 00:38:44.525
You can be super
funny and silly.

00:38:44.525 --> 00:38:46.950
That'll get you some points.

00:38:46.950 --> 00:38:48.210
But you can't be sad.

00:38:48.210 --> 00:38:50.904
You can't be afraid.

00:38:50.904 --> 00:38:53.070
And so what I've experienced,
in working with adults

00:38:53.070 --> 00:38:55.350
and working with
parents, is that, if you

00:38:55.350 --> 00:38:58.740
don't find a place--
it may not be at work,

00:38:58.740 --> 00:39:01.270
but if you don't find a place
that you can go regularly

00:39:01.270 --> 00:39:04.090
to be like, let me just talk
about what's really going--

00:39:04.090 --> 00:39:12.920
not to be fixed, but just to
be heard, just to be seen,

00:39:12.920 --> 00:39:16.366
I believe that we do
ourselves a disservice.

00:39:16.366 --> 00:39:18.490
If you're a manager and
you're working with people,

00:39:18.490 --> 00:39:20.406
and you've got people
in your team who may not

00:39:20.406 --> 00:39:22.110
be doing everything
the way they should

00:39:22.110 --> 00:39:27.010
or whatever, maybe you
could ask, how's it going?

00:39:27.010 --> 00:39:30.767
Can we just have a real talk?

00:39:30.767 --> 00:39:32.100
That's why I don't say get real.

00:39:32.100 --> 00:39:34.886
Getting real is like, can I talk
about what's really going on

00:39:34.886 --> 00:39:36.260
and feel safe that
it's not going

00:39:36.260 --> 00:39:41.700
to jeopardize my valuation,
or my status among my team.

00:39:44.670 --> 00:39:51.040
It wasn't until I joined a men's
team, in 2010, that I really

00:39:51.040 --> 00:39:56.120
felt like I was being seen by
other men that were pushing me

00:39:56.120 --> 00:40:01.460
to be better, like I could
talk about successes at work

00:40:01.460 --> 00:40:04.480
and people were not
like, oh, whatever.

00:40:04.480 --> 00:40:06.270
It was like, yeah!

00:40:06.270 --> 00:40:06.770
Nice!

00:40:09.590 --> 00:40:12.210
That's powerful.

00:40:12.210 --> 00:40:14.080
It's powerful to
be knowing that you

00:40:14.080 --> 00:40:17.470
could have people around you who
care about you being the best

00:40:17.470 --> 00:40:18.320
you.

00:40:18.320 --> 00:40:21.490
So they help you
through the down times,

00:40:21.490 --> 00:40:23.160
because the only
way to move back up

00:40:23.160 --> 00:40:25.220
is to get through
the down times.

00:40:25.220 --> 00:40:26.600
We're all going to have them.

00:40:26.600 --> 00:40:28.600
But if we're always
pretending like everything's

00:40:28.600 --> 00:40:30.700
always perfect, then when
do we ever get support

00:40:30.700 --> 00:40:36.045
to get stronger, to get better?

00:40:36.045 --> 00:40:38.360
So if you don't
have that, I would

00:40:38.360 --> 00:40:41.016
